                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d16">
                <head>16. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Burma</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d16fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 411.90B41/9–755. Secret; Priority. Repeated to Tokyo.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Rangoon</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1955-09-07T19:00:00+06:30">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 7, 1955—7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>226. Reference: Paragraph 4, Department telegram 142.<note n="2" xml:id="d16fn2"
                        >Telegram 142 to Rangoon, August 20, set forth guidelines for the Embassy’s
                        use in informal conversations concerning a possible U.S. loan to Burma.
                        Paragraph 4 concerned the possibility of assistance through Public Law
                        480—the United States would supply cotton (to be processed into textiles in
                        third countries) and other commodities to Burma as a means of supplying
                        consumer goods and defraying the local currency cost of Burma’s development
                        program. (<hi rend="italic">Ibid.,</hi> 890B.10/8–1755)</note> Ministers
                        <persName corresp="#p_KNU1">U Kyaw Nyein</persName> (Industries) and
                        <persName>U Raschid</persName> (Trade Development) today asked me explore
                    possibility <gloss target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> 480 agreement. View trade ties
                    with Communist countries, <gloss target="#t_GUB1">GUB</gloss> first wishes
                    clarify whether Battle Act or Section 304 <gloss target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss>
                        480<note n="3" xml:id="d16fn3">Section 304 of Public Law 480 required that
                        the sale or transfer of agricultural commodities under the act did not
                        result in increased availability of those commodities to unfriendly
                        nations.</note> would prevent either agreement as a whole or loan under
                    Section 104(g).<note n="4" xml:id="d16fn4">Section 104(g) of Public Law 480
                        authorized agreements to use foreign currencies that accrued to the United
                        States under the act for loans to promote trade and economic
                        development.</note> Both Ministers emphasized importance these
                    considerations to Burma.</p>
                <p>In reply question whether Burmese rubber exports to Communist China were due to
                    political decision to accommodate <gloss target="#t_CPR1">CPR</gloss> or
                    economic decision to exploit good market they said Burma had trade <pb
                        facs="0051" n="23" xml:id="pg_23"/> agreement obligation provide certain
                    materials including rubber to <gloss target="#t_CPR1">CPR</gloss>. Moreover
                        <gloss target="#t_CPR1">CPR</gloss> was paying Burma ten percent above world
                    price for rubber. I sensed that <gloss target="#t_GUB1">GUB</gloss> would not
                    pursue <gloss target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> 480 program if program conditioned on
                        <gloss target="#t_GUB1">GUB</gloss> renunciation of freedom sell its
                    products Communist countries.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_GUB1">GUB</gloss> interested $20 million program breakdown not
                    yet made, but would be 75 percent or more cotton (Japan indicated for processing
                    into textiles), balance dairy products, wheat, flour and tobacco.</p>
                <p>Agricultural Attaché Quate, who with <persName corresp="#p_BDM1"
                        >Braddock</persName> and <persName>Phillips</persName>
                    <note n="5" xml:id="d16fn5">
                        <persName corresp="#p_BDM1">Daniel M. Braddock</persName>, Counselor of
                        Embassy; <persName>Robert M. Phillips</persName>, Second Secretary.</note>
                    accompanied me, answered questions regarding procedures and operations <gloss
                        target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> 480 programs.</p>
                <p>Request Department’s comments soonest.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SJC1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Satterthwaite</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
